GREENWOOD, Miss. (AP) — A school district in the Mississippi Delta is hiring three consulting firms to improve its curriculum and instructional strategies after a drop in test scores. The board of the Greenwood Leflore Consolidated School District on Tuesday approved nearly $400,000 in payments to the education firms for help in English language arts, history, math and science, the Greenwood Commonwealth reported.Results from the Mississippi Academic Assessment Program administered earlier this year showed a drop in the district’s English and math proficiency levels. Students across the state experienced a similar fall off in scores.The district will pay $123,500 to the Excellence Group to improve professional development services in English language arts, $65,000 to Kids First for history, another $97,500 to Kids First for science and $104,000 to Kirkland for math.